## What Problem This Solves

`openclaw doctor --fix` upgrades retired model refs in config. For a `models` map (keyed by model ref, such as `agents.defaults.models` and per-agent `agents.list[].models`), `rewriteModelRefMapKeys` rewrites each key to its current ref. When two retired keys upgrade to the SAME current ref, the second entry is silently dropped with no merge and no warning.

`src/commands/doctor/shared/legacy-config-migrations.runtime.models.ts` before:

```ts
if (nextKey in next && upgradedKey) {
  continue;
}
next[nextKey] = child;
```

Many retired ids collapse to one current ref. For example both `openai/gpt-4o` and `openai/gpt-4` upgrade to `openai/gpt-5.5`. A user who keeps distinct per-model tuning under two such keys (different `params`, `streaming`, `alias`, `agentRuntime`) loses one entry's entire config. Worse, the change log already pushed a success line for the dropped key (`Upgraded ... key from X to Y.`), so the migration report FALSELY claims the dropped key was upgraded.

## Why This Change Was Made

The sibling provider-models-array path in this same file (issue #90047, `migrateLegacyOpenAICodexProvider`) already merges disjoint entries on collision and warns when a safe merge is impossible, rather than dropping. The map-key path was the unguarded sibling. This change applies the same merge-or-warn semantics so a doctor migration never silently destroys user config.

`rewriteModelRefMapKeys` after, on a key collision:

```ts
if (nextKey in next && upgradedKey) {
  const { value, conflicts } = mergeModelRefMapEntries(next[nextKey], child);
  next[nextKey] = value;
  if (conflicts.length > 0) {
    changes.push(
      `Merged ${path} key ${JSON.stringify(key)} into ${JSON.stringify(nextKey)}; kept existing values for conflicting fields: ${conflicts.join(", ")}.`,
    );
  } else {
    changes.push(`Merged ${path} key ${JSON.stringify(key)} into ${JSON.stringify(nextKey)}.`);
  }
  continue;
}
```

`mergeModelRefMapEntries` deep-merges the two entries: disjoint fields are preserved, nested records (`params`, `agentRuntime`) merge recursively, and when a scalar field is defined on both with different values the existing value is kept deterministically and the field is named in a collision change-log line. No entry is ever silently dropped.

## User Impact

After upgrading and running the standard `openclaw doctor --fix`, users who had two retired model-ref keys collapsing to one current ref keep both entries' tuning instead of losing one. The change log reports a truthful merge/collision line instead of a false success.

## Why this is the right boundary

This is doctor/migration code, the only place legacy config shapes are normalized, so the fix lives where ownership belongs. It reuses the existing `getRecord` and `hasOwnDefinedProperty` helpers and mirrors the already-merged sibling array path; existing single-key upgrades and the existing change-log success lines for non-colliding keys are unchanged. The other model-ref surfaces (string keys, array keys) cannot collide because they do not key a map.

## Real behavior proof

Behavior addressed: doctor --fix collapsed two retired model-map keys to one current ref and silently dropped the second entry's entire tuning while logging a false upgrade-success line.
Real environment tested: the real `migrateLegacyConfig` entry point driven on identical input on pristine main 3848b9619fdb42eb7a3b76dff80b93e0911c17c4 and on the patched tree; the real migration pipeline, real upgrade map, and real change-log all stayed real with no external seam mocked.
Exact steps or command run after this patch: invoke `migrateLegacyConfig` with `agents.defaults.models = { "openai/gpt-4o": { params: { reasoning_effort: "high" }, streaming: false }, "openai/gpt-4": { params: { reasoning_effort: "low" }, alias: "legacy-four" } }` and print the surviving map plus its change-log lines.
Evidence after fix:
```
# BEFORE (pristine main 3848b9619fdb42eb7a3b76dff80b93e0911c17c4)
surviving agents.defaults.models =
{
  "openai/gpt-5.5": {
    "params": {
      "reasoning_effort": "high"
    },
    "streaming": false
  }
}
change-log lines for this map:
  Upgraded config.agents.defaults.models key from "openai/gpt-4o" to "openai/gpt-5.5".
  Upgraded config.agents.defaults.models key from "openai/gpt-4" to "openai/gpt-5.5".

# AFTER (this patch, identical input)
surviving agents.defaults.models =
{
  "openai/gpt-5.5": {
    "alias": "legacy-four",
    "params": {
      "reasoning_effort": "high"
    },
    "streaming": false
  }
}
change-log lines for this map:
  Upgraded config.agents.defaults.models key from "openai/gpt-4o" to "openai/gpt-5.5".
  Upgraded config.agents.defaults.models key from "openai/gpt-4" to "openai/gpt-5.5".
  Merged config.agents.defaults.models key "openai/gpt-4" into "openai/gpt-5.5"; kept existing values for conflicting fields: params.reasoning_effort.
```
Observed result after fix: the merged entry keeps the disjoint `streaming: false` and `alias: "legacy-four"` from both keys, the conflicting `params.reasoning_effort` resolves deterministically to the existing value, and the report names the merge instead of falsely claiming a clean upgrade of the dropped key.
What was not tested: no live end-to-end CLI invocation of the full `openclaw doctor --fix` command; the migration function was driven directly with identical input. Full build not run.

## Verification

- `node scripts/run-vitest.mjs src/commands/doctor/shared/legacy-config-migrate.test.ts`: 116 passed (new collision-merge test plus the existing suite).
- New test `merges colliding model ref map keys instead of dropping per-key tuning` fails on pristine main (surviving entry has only 2 fields, `alias`/`low` tuning lost) and passes with the patch.
- `node scripts/run-oxlint.mjs <changed files>`: clean.
- `oxfmt --check <changed files>`: clean.
- `node scripts/run-tsgo.mjs -p tsconfig.core.json` and `-p test/tsconfig/tsconfig.core.test.json`: clean.
